1
00:00:11,520 --> 00:00:12,800
(ALARM SOUNDING)

2
00:00:12,880 --> 00:00:14,800
WOMAN: Would all passengers
please return to their seats

3
00:00:14,880 --> 00:00:19,160
and fasten their safety belts.
We are experiencing slight turbulence.

4
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:22,920
Both engines failed and
the storm gate's critical.

5
00:00:23,480 --> 00:00:26,520
The ship is going down.
Christmas is cancelled.

6
00:00:28,880 --> 00:00:30,040
Entering atmosphere now.

7
00:00:32,080 --> 00:00:33,360
Level! Keep her level!

8
00:00:33,440 --> 00:00:35,360
With what? I can't see.

9
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:38,000
What's that stuff?

10
00:00:38,240 --> 00:00:39,440
Clouds?

11
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:41,360
What kind of clouds?

12
00:00:41,840 --> 00:00:42,920
Are you sending a distress signal?

13
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:44,080
Ah!

14
00:00:44,160 --> 00:00:45,560
It's not me.

15
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:48,640
Who's in the honeymoon suite?

16
00:00:53,160 --> 00:00:54,600
-I've sent for help.
-Who the hell are you?

17
00:00:54,680 --> 00:00:57,240
Look, there's a friend of mine, okay?
And he can help us. He'll come.

18
00:00:57,320 --> 00:00:58,680
And what are you wearing?

19
00:00:58,760 --> 00:01:00,440
That doesn't matter.

20
00:01:00,520 --> 00:01:01,560
Are you from the honeymoon suite?

21
00:01:01,640 --> 00:01:03,120
Oh... Shut up.

22
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:07,480
Oh! Amy! The light's stopped flashing.
Does that mean he's coming?

23
00:01:08,080 --> 00:01:09,680
-Honeymoon suite?
-Oh...

24
00:01:09,760 --> 00:01:12,960
Oh, the clothes. Um...
It is just a bit of fun.

25
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:14,600
Rory, shut up!

26
00:01:14,880 --> 00:01:16,760
Excessive oscillating
in the centre hull.

27
00:01:16,840 --> 00:01:19,720
I'm sorry, does this mean he's coming or
does it mean I need to change the bulb?

28
00:01:19,800 --> 00:01:21,560
He'll come. He always comes.

29
00:01:21,640 --> 00:01:23,240
Right, well, he is cutting it
kind of fine.

30
00:01:23,320 --> 00:01:25,520
If we can't stabilise the orbit,
we're finished.

31
00:01:25,600 --> 00:01:27,920
MAN 1: There's nothing to lock on to.
MAN 2: I'm flying blind.

32
00:01:30,040 --> 00:01:31,960
Come on, Doctor. Come on.

33
00:01:32,040 --> 00:01:34,760
There's something coming alongside us.
Something small, like a shuttle.

34
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:35,880
Just this once, don't be late.

35
00:01:35,960 --> 00:01:39,640
Ma'am, incoming message.
It's from the other ship.

36
00:01:39,720 --> 00:01:41,040
On screen.

37
00:01:45,760 --> 00:01:47,240
What does that mean?

38
00:01:47,320 --> 00:01:48,840
It's Christmas.

39
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:51,640
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

40
00:02:37,400 --> 00:02:40,880
Get your Chronicle here.
Sardicktown Chronicle!

41
00:02:45,760 --> 00:02:47,160
Here you go.

42
00:02:49,320 --> 00:02:52,160
MAN: On every world,
wherever people are,

43
00:02:52,240 --> 00:02:57,400
in the deepest part of the winter,
at the exact midpoint,

44
00:02:57,480 --> 00:03:01,640
everybody stops and turns and hugs,

45
00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:04,160
as if to say, "Well done!

46
00:03:04,640 --> 00:03:06,640
"Well done, everyone!

47
00:03:07,320 --> 00:03:09,880
"We're halfway out of the dark.”

48
00:03:15,480 --> 00:03:18,760
Back on Earth, we call this Christmas,

49
00:03:19,640 --> 00:03:21,560
or the winter solstice.

50
00:03:26,160 --> 00:03:30,440
On this world, the first settlers
called it the Crystal Feast.

51
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:33,040
You know what I call it?

52
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:35,920
I call it expecting something
for nothing!

53
00:03:37,920 --> 00:03:41,400
Sir? Mr Sardick,
we're only asking for one day.

54
00:03:41,480 --> 00:03:43,960
Just let her out for Christmas.

55
00:03:45,720 --> 00:03:46,960
She loves Christmas.

56
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:51,320
Does she? Oh, does she? I see.

57
00:03:51,400 --> 00:03:54,440
Hello! Oh, wakey, wakey!

58
00:03:54,520 --> 00:03:56,440
It's Christmas!

59
00:03:57,080 --> 00:04:01,480
Do you know what? I think
she's a bit cool about the whole thing.

60
00:04:01,720 --> 00:04:03,120
(LAUGHING)

61
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:06,840
That was funny.

62
00:04:06,920 --> 00:04:08,800
(LAUGHING)

63
00:04:08,880 --> 00:04:10,200
BOY: She's frozen.

64
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:11,760
She's what, sorry?

65
00:04:11,840 --> 00:04:14,160
She's in the ice. She can't hear you.

66
00:04:14,240 --> 00:04:16,840
Oh, what a clever little boy.

67
00:04:18,080 --> 00:04:20,120
You must be so irritated.

68
00:04:20,520 --> 00:04:21,840
How much?

69
00:04:21,920 --> 00:04:24,320
Uh, it's, uh, 4,500 gideons, sir.

70
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:27,720
You took a loan of 4,500 gideons

71
00:04:27,800 --> 00:04:31,560
and little Miss Christmas
is my security.

72
00:04:31,920 --> 00:04:34,720
We're not asking for her back.
Just let her have one day.

73
00:04:34,800 --> 00:04:36,440
Let her have Christmas with us.

74
00:04:36,520 --> 00:04:39,320
Sir, it's the, uh, president.

75
00:04:39,560 --> 00:04:40,800
Tell him I'm busy.

76
00:04:41,320 --> 00:04:42,360
Now...

77
00:04:42,440 --> 00:04:43,680
(CHUCKLING)

78
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:44,800
Where were we?

79
00:04:44,880 --> 00:04:48,440
Oh, yes.
She's pretty, though, your daughter.

80
00:04:49,240 --> 00:04:51,160
Maybe I should keep her.

81
00:04:51,240 --> 00:04:52,920
She's not my daughter, sir.

82
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:54,280
She's my sister.

83
00:04:54,360 --> 00:04:55,520
She volunteered for the ice

84
00:04:55,600 --> 00:04:58,400
when the family were in difficulties
many years ago.

85
00:04:58,480 --> 00:05:01,720
Sorry, sir, the president says
there's a Galaxy-class ship

86
00:05:01,800 --> 00:05:04,560
trapped in the cloud layer and,
well, we have to let it land.

87
00:05:04,640 --> 00:05:05,840
Or?

88
00:05:05,920 --> 00:05:08,080
Well... Or it'll crash, sir.

89
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:11,600
Oh. Well, it's a kind of landing,
isn't it?

90
00:05:12,120 --> 00:05:16,000
It's from Earth, sir, registering
over 4,000 life forms on board.

91
00:05:16,080 --> 00:05:17,160
(LAUGHING)

92
00:05:17,240 --> 00:05:18,800
KAZRAN: Not if we wait a bit.

93
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:21,160
MAN: We can't just let it crash, sir.

94
00:05:21,240 --> 00:05:22,480
KAZRAN: Says who?

95
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:23,640
(WHOOSHING)

96
00:05:23,720 --> 00:05:25,440
Oh, give it here.

97
00:05:25,520 --> 00:05:28,640
Look, petal, we already have
a surplus population.

98
00:05:28,720 --> 00:05:31,360
No more people allowed on this planet.

99
00:05:31,480 --> 00:05:33,080
-I don't make the rules.
-Huh?

100
00:05:33,160 --> 00:05:35,400
Oh, no, hang on. I do.

101
00:05:36,360 --> 00:05:38,240
All right, you lot.

102
00:05:38,320 --> 00:05:41,800
Poor, begging people.
Off home and pray for a miracle.

103
00:05:51,360 --> 00:05:53,560
(COUGHING)

104
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:55,920
Ah!

105
00:05:56,600 --> 00:05:58,840
Yes! Blimey, sorry!

106
00:05:58,920 --> 00:06:00,720
Christmas Eve on a rooftop,
saw a chimney,

107
00:06:00,800 --> 00:06:03,480
my whole brain just went,
"What the hell?"

108
00:06:03,560 --> 00:06:05,960
Don't worry, fat fella will be
doing the rounds later.

109
00:06:06,040 --> 00:06:09,840
I'm just scoping out the general...
chimneyness! Yes!

110
00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:12,600
Nice size. Good traction.

111
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:14,000
(SIZZLING)

112
00:06:14,360 --> 00:06:15,480
Big take.

113
00:06:15,560 --> 00:06:17,520
-Fat fella?
-Father Christmas.

114
00:06:17,600 --> 00:06:20,920
Santa Claus,
or, as I've always known him, Jeff.

115
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,080
There's no such person
as Father Christmas.

116
00:06:23,160 --> 00:06:28,080
Oh, yeah? Me and Father Christmas,
Frank Sinatra's hunting lodge, 1952.

117
00:06:28,160 --> 00:06:29,480
See him at the back with the blonde?

118
00:06:29,560 --> 00:06:31,360
Albert Einstein,
the three of us together.

119
00:06:31,440 --> 00:06:34,560
Vroom! Watch out! Okay?

120
00:06:35,720 --> 00:06:38,480
Keep the faith.
Stay off the naughtiness.

121
00:06:38,560 --> 00:06:40,400
Ooh, now what's this, then? I love this.

122
00:06:40,480 --> 00:06:42,880
A big, flashy lighty thing,
that's what brought me here.

123
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:44,960
Big, flashy lighty things have got me
written all over them.

124
00:06:45,040 --> 00:06:47,240
Not actually,
but give me time and a crayon.

125
00:06:47,320 --> 00:06:49,160
Now, this big, flashy lighty thing
is connected

126
00:06:49,240 --> 00:06:53,320
to the spire in your dome, yeah?
And it controls the sky.

127
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:55,360
Well, technically,
it controls the clouds,

128
00:06:55,440 --> 00:06:57,840
which technically aren't clouds at all.

129
00:06:57,920 --> 00:07:00,800
Well, they're clouds
of tiny particles of ice.

130
00:07:00,880 --> 00:07:03,280
Ice clouds, love that. Who's she?

131
00:07:03,480 --> 00:07:04,600
Nobody important.

132
00:07:04,680 --> 00:07:06,720
Nobody important!

133
00:07:07,200 --> 00:07:09,360
Blimey, that's amazing.

134
00:07:09,800 --> 00:07:11,560
Do you know,
in 900 years of time and space,

135
00:07:11,640 --> 00:07:14,400
I've never met anyone
who wasn't important before?

136
00:07:15,320 --> 00:07:18,520
Now, this console is the key
to saving that ship

137
00:07:18,880 --> 00:07:21,680
or I'll eat my hat, if I had a hat.

138
00:07:21,760 --> 00:07:23,520
I'll eat someone's hat,
not someone who's using their hat,

139
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:24,920
I don't want to shock a man
or something.

140
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:27,440
Sorry, rambling.
That's because this isn't working!

141
00:07:27,520 --> 00:07:31,640
Controls are isomorphic, one-to-one.
They respond only to me.

142
00:07:31,720 --> 00:07:36,280
Oh, you fibber! Isomorphic!
There's no such thing.

143
00:07:38,320 --> 00:07:39,960
(SYSTEM POWERING DOWN)

144
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:45,440
(SYSTEM REVVING UP)

145
00:07:50,840 --> 00:07:51,960
(WARBLING)

146
00:07:56,120 --> 00:07:57,720
These controls are isomorphic.

147
00:07:57,800 --> 00:08:00,160
The skies of this entire world are mine.

148
00:08:00,240 --> 00:08:02,840
My family tamed them and now I own them.

149
00:08:02,920 --> 00:08:05,720
Tamed the sky? What does that mean?

150
00:08:05,840 --> 00:08:08,800
It means I'm Kazran Sardick.

151
00:08:10,160 --> 00:08:12,960
How could he possibly not know who I am?

152
00:08:13,680 --> 00:08:17,000
Well, just easily bored, I suppose.

153
00:08:17,640 --> 00:08:19,760
So, I need your help, then.

154
00:08:19,880 --> 00:08:21,640
Make an appointment.

155
00:08:22,240 --> 00:08:25,440
There are 4,003 people in a spaceship
trapped in your cloud belt.

156
00:08:25,520 --> 00:08:27,880
Without your help, they're going to die.

157
00:08:27,960 --> 00:08:29,040
Yes.

158
00:08:30,640 --> 00:08:32,160
You don't have to let that happen.

159
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:33,640
I know, but I'm going to.

160
00:08:33,720 --> 00:08:35,760
Bye-bye. Bored now. Chuck!

161
00:08:40,080 --> 00:08:42,240
Oh, look at you, looking all tough now.

162
00:08:42,320 --> 00:08:44,800
There are 4,003 people
I won't allow to die tonight.

163
00:08:44,880 --> 00:08:45,920
Do you know where that puts you?

164
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,160
Where?

165
00:08:48,040 --> 00:08:49,440
4,004,

166
00:08:49,520 --> 00:08:51,560
Was that a sort of threaty thing?

167
00:08:51,640 --> 00:08:54,120
Whatever happens tonight, remember,

168
00:08:55,240 --> 00:08:56,760
you brought it on yourself.

169
00:08:56,840 --> 00:08:59,520
Yeah, yeah, right. Get him out of here!

170
00:09:00,240 --> 00:09:03,680
And next time, try and find me
some funny poor people.

171
00:09:04,720 --> 00:09:06,040
(YELPS)

172
00:09:09,080 --> 00:09:11,200
-No! Stop!
-Don't you dare! You leave him!

173
00:09:11,280 --> 00:09:12,360
(GASPS)

174
00:09:17,280 --> 00:09:18,640
Get them out of here!

175
00:09:18,720 --> 00:09:21,720
Get that foul smelling family
out of here! Out!

176
00:09:22,440 --> 00:09:23,840
BOY: We're going!

177
00:09:28,360 --> 00:09:30,160
What? What do you want?

178
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:32,360
A simple life.

179
00:09:33,160 --> 00:09:34,640
But you didn't hit the boy.

180
00:09:34,720 --> 00:09:36,080
Well, I will next time.

181
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:38,400
You see, you won't. Now, why?

182
00:09:39,640 --> 00:09:41,360
What am I missing?

183
00:09:41,720 --> 00:09:44,000
Get out! Get out of this house!

184
00:09:45,040 --> 00:09:47,720
The chairs. Of course, the chairs.
Stupid me. The chairs.

185
00:09:47,800 --> 00:09:49,000
Chairs?

186
00:09:49,440 --> 00:09:50,720
There's a portrait
on the wall behind me,

187
00:09:50,800 --> 00:09:52,560
looks like you, but it's too old,
so it's your father.

188
00:09:52,640 --> 00:09:54,960
All the chairs are angled away from it.
Daddy's been dead for 20 years

189
00:09:55,040 --> 00:09:57,080
but you still can't get comfortable
where he can see you.

190
00:09:57,160 --> 00:09:58,440
There's a Christmas tree
in the painting,

191
00:09:58,520 --> 00:09:59,840
but none in this house on Christmas Eve.

192
00:09:59,920 --> 00:10:01,840
You're scared of him,
and you're scared of being like him,

193
00:10:01,920 --> 00:10:05,280
and good for you, you're not like him,
not really. Do you know why?

194
00:10:05,360 --> 00:10:06,440
Why?

195
00:10:07,880 --> 00:10:10,160
Because you didn't hit the boy.

196
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:13,840
Merry Christmas, Mr Sardick.

197
00:10:13,920 --> 00:10:15,400
I despise Christmas.

198
00:10:17,680 --> 00:10:19,480
Shouldn't. It's very you.

199
00:10:19,800 --> 00:10:21,960
It's what? What do you mean?

200
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:25,760
Halfway out of the dark.

201
00:10:31,840 --> 00:10:35,560
Get her downstairs with the others!
And clean up this mess!

202
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:40,640
MAN 1: I'm still blind!

203
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:41,880
Secondary burn shield vented.

204
00:10:41,960 --> 00:10:43,840
-Have you got a plan yet?
-Yes, I do.

205
00:10:44,520 --> 00:10:45,640
Are you lying?

206
00:10:45,720 --> 00:10:46,760
Yes, I am.

207
00:10:46,840 --> 00:10:48,240
Don't treat me like an idiot.

208
00:10:48,360 --> 00:10:49,440
Is he lying?

209
00:10:49,520 --> 00:10:50,560
(LAUGHING)

210
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:52,160
-No, no.
-DOCTOR: Okay.

211
00:10:52,240 --> 00:10:54,440
The good news, I've tracked the machine
that unlocks the cloud belt,

212
00:10:54,520 --> 00:10:57,240
I could use it to clear your flight
corridor and you could land, easily.

213
00:10:57,320 --> 00:10:59,360
Well, hey, hey, that's great news.

214
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:01,040
But I can't control the machine.

215
00:11:01,120 --> 00:11:02,400
Less great.

216
00:11:02,480 --> 00:11:04,240
-But I met a man who can.
-Ah, well, there you go.

217
00:11:04,320 --> 00:11:06,960
-And he hates me.
-Were you extra charming and clever?

218
00:11:07,040 --> 00:11:08,960
-Yeah, how did you know?
-Lucky guess.

219
00:11:09,040 --> 00:11:10,600
Sir? Sir?

220
00:11:10,680 --> 00:11:11,760
Hang on.

221
00:11:11,840 --> 00:11:14,520
I've never seen anybody
stand up to Mr Sardick like that.

222
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:16,360
Bless you, sir. And merry Christmas.

223
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:18,480
Merry Christmas.
Lovely, sorry, a bit busy.

224
00:11:18,560 --> 00:11:19,680
You'd better get inside, sir.

225
00:11:19,760 --> 00:11:21,160
The fog's thick tonight
and there's a fish warning.

226
00:11:21,240 --> 00:11:22,840
All right, yeah. Sorry, fish?

227
00:11:22,920 --> 00:11:24,720
Yeah, you know what they're like
when they get a bit hungry.

228
00:11:24,800 --> 00:11:26,480
Yeah, fish, I know, fish. Fish?

229
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:28,520
It's all Mr Sardick's fault, I reckon.

230
00:11:28,600 --> 00:11:33,080
He always lets a few fish through the
cloud layer when he's in a bad mood.

231
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:35,920
Thank you,
and bless you once again, sir.

232
00:11:37,160 --> 00:11:38,200
Fish?

233
00:11:39,280 --> 00:11:41,160
Doctor, the captain says
we've got less than an hour.

234
00:11:41,240 --> 00:11:43,200
What should we be doing?

235
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:46,200
Fish.

236
00:11:46,280 --> 00:11:47,920
AMY: Sorry, what?

237
00:11:49,720 --> 00:11:52,000
Fish that can swim in fog.

238
00:11:53,560 --> 00:11:55,440
I love new planets.

239
00:11:55,520 --> 00:11:57,480
Doctor... Doctor, please,
don't get distracted.

240
00:11:57,560 --> 00:12:01,760
Now, why would people be frightened
of you tiny, little fellas?

241
00:12:01,840 --> 00:12:04,840
Look at you,
sweet, little fishy-wishies.

242
00:12:06,960 --> 00:12:10,360
Mind you, fish in the fog,
so the cloud cover... Ooh.

243
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:11,760
Careful up there!

244
00:12:12,560 --> 00:12:14,280
Oh. Oh, great, thanks, Doctor,

245
00:12:14,360 --> 00:12:16,280
because there was a real danger
we were all going to nod off.

246
00:12:16,360 --> 00:12:17,760
We've got less than an hour!

247
00:12:19,120 --> 00:12:20,360
DOCTOR: I know.

248
00:12:20,640 --> 00:12:23,040
(DING DONG MERRILY ON HIGH PLAYING)

249
00:12:23,120 --> 00:12:24,880
Doctor, how are you getting us off here?

250
00:12:24,960 --> 00:12:26,640
Oh, just give me a minute!

251
00:12:26,720 --> 00:12:27,880
Can't use the Tardis,
'cause it can't lock on.

252
00:12:27,960 --> 00:12:29,720
So that ship needs to land,
but it can't land

253
00:12:29,800 --> 00:12:31,720
unless a very bad man
suddenly decides to turn nice

254
00:12:31,800 --> 00:12:32,840
just in time for Christmas Day.

255
00:12:32,920 --> 00:12:35,760
Doctor, I can't hear you.
What is that? Is that singing?

256
00:12:35,840 --> 00:12:37,440
-A Christmas carol.
-A what?

257
00:12:37,520 --> 00:12:39,440
-A Christmas carol.
-A what?

258
00:12:39,520 --> 00:12:41,200
A Christmas carol!

259
00:12:43,160 --> 00:12:44,560
AMY: Doctor?

260
00:12:47,280 --> 00:12:49,480
-Kazran Sardick.
-AMY: Doctor!

261
00:12:51,280 --> 00:12:53,840
Merry Christmas, Kazran Sardick.

262
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:06,000
(SNORING)

263
00:13:09,640 --> 00:13:10,760
Hello.

264
00:13:11,240 --> 00:13:14,440
My name is Kazran Sardick.
I'm twelve and a half.

265
00:13:15,040 --> 00:13:16,480
And this is my bedroom.

266
00:13:17,600 --> 00:13:18,960
(GRUNTING)

267
00:13:19,040 --> 00:13:20,840
Top-secret special project.

268
00:13:22,080 --> 00:13:25,840
This is my top-secret special project,
for my eyes only.

269
00:13:26,480 --> 00:13:28,480
-Merry Christmas.
-ELLIOT: Kazran! Kazran!

270
00:13:30,080 --> 00:13:32,600
Kazran, what are you doing?

271
00:13:32,920 --> 00:13:34,640
What are you doing?

272
00:13:36,920 --> 00:13:38,520
I've warned you before about this.

273
00:13:38,600 --> 00:13:41,240
Stupid, ignorant, ridiculous child!

274
00:13:41,320 --> 00:13:43,560
YOUNG KAZRAN: I was just going to
make a film of the fish.

275
00:13:43,640 --> 00:13:45,280
ELLIOT: Fish are dangerous!

276
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:47,040
I just want to see them.

277
00:13:47,120 --> 00:13:48,800
Don't be stupid. You're far too young.

278
00:13:48,880 --> 00:13:51,360
YOUNG KAZRAN:
Everyone at school's seen the fish.

279
00:13:51,440 --> 00:13:55,520
ELLIOT: 7hat's enough. You'll be singing
to them next, like gypsies.

280
00:13:55,600 --> 00:13:59,280
Singing works. I've seen It.
The fish like the singing.

281
00:13:59,360 --> 00:14:01,600
ELLIOT: What does it matter
what fish like?

282
00:14:01,680 --> 00:14:04,800
YOUNG KAZRAN: People say we don't
have to be afraid of the fish.

283
00:14:04,880 --> 00:14:06,080
They're not really interested in us.

284
00:14:06,160 --> 00:14:09,120
You don't listen to people!
You listen to me!

285
00:14:09,400 --> 00:14:10,920
(YOUNG KAZRAN YELPS)

286
00:14:11,920 --> 00:14:13,400
YOUNG KAZRAN: Sorry, Father.

287
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:15,240
(ELLIOT SHOUTING)

288
00:14:18,720 --> 00:14:20,000
(SOBBING)

289
00:14:22,440 --> 00:14:24,240
It's okay. It's okay.

290
00:14:24,320 --> 00:14:26,720
What have you done? What is this?

291
00:14:27,120 --> 00:14:29,360
Found it on an old drive.
Sorry about the picture quality.

292
00:14:29,440 --> 00:14:33,560
Had to recover the data using quantum
enfolding and a paper clip.

293
00:14:36,360 --> 00:14:39,040
Oh, I wouldn't bother
calling your servants. They quit.

294
00:14:39,120 --> 00:14:42,280
Apparently, they won the lottery
at exactly the same time,

295
00:14:42,360 --> 00:14:44,360
which is a bit lucky,
when you think about it.

296
00:14:44,440 --> 00:14:45,480
There isn't a lottery.

297
00:14:45,560 --> 00:14:47,880
Yeah, as I say, lucky.

298
00:14:47,960 --> 00:14:49,920
ELLIOT: 7here's a fog warning tonight.

299
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:53,440
You keep these windows
closed. understand? Closed!

300
00:14:53,520 --> 00:14:54,640
(YOUNG KAZRAN SOBBING)

301
00:14:54,720 --> 00:14:55,760
Who are you?

302
00:14:55,840 --> 00:14:59,880
Tonight,
I'm the Ghost of Christmas Past.

303
00:14:59,960 --> 00:15:03,000
ELLIOT: Mrs Mantovani will be
looking after you tonight.

304
00:15:03,080 --> 00:15:05,280
You stay here 'til she comes.

305
00:15:06,200 --> 00:15:08,840
Do you understand? Do you understand?

306
00:15:13,600 --> 00:15:17,440
DOCTOR: Did you ever get to see a fish
back then when you were a kid?

307
00:15:17,560 --> 00:15:19,800
What does that matter to you?

308
00:15:20,840 --> 00:15:22,360
Look how it mattered to you.

309
00:15:22,440 --> 00:15:23,720
(SOBBING)

310
00:15:23,840 --> 00:15:25,520
I cried all night

311
00:15:26,600 --> 00:15:28,960
and I learnt life's
most invaluable lesson.

312
00:15:29,040 --> 00:15:30,080
Ah.

313
00:15:30,400 --> 00:15:31,520
Which is?

314
00:15:31,600 --> 00:15:33,520
Nobody comes.

315
00:15:36,480 --> 00:15:37,720
Get out! Get out of my house!

316
00:15:37,800 --> 00:15:40,400
Okay! I'll go, but I'll be back.

317
00:15:41,480 --> 00:15:42,760
Way back.

318
00:15:46,200 --> 00:15:47,680
Way, way back.

319
00:15:49,640 --> 00:15:50,920
(SOBBING)

320
00:15:53,960 --> 00:15:55,760
(WHOOSHING)

321
00:16:03,320 --> 00:16:04,680
See? Back.

322
00:16:07,080 --> 00:16:09,640
-YOUNG KAZRAN: Who are you?
-Hi I'm the Doctor.

323
00:16:09,720 --> 00:16:11,200
I'm your new babysitter.

324
00:16:11,280 --> 00:16:12,440
Where's Mrs Mantovani?

325
00:16:12,520 --> 00:16:13,600
Ah, you'll never guess.

326
00:16:13,680 --> 00:16:16,320
Clever old Mrs Manto,
she only went and won the lottery.

327
00:16:16,400 --> 00:16:18,040
There isn't any lottery!

328
00:16:18,120 --> 00:16:20,760
-There isn't any lottery.
-I know! What a woman!

329
00:16:20,840 --> 00:16:23,440
YOUNG KAZRAN: If you're my babysitter,
why are you climbing in the window?

330
00:16:23,520 --> 00:16:25,840
If I was climbing out the window,
I'd be going in the wrong direction.

331
00:16:25,920 --> 00:16:27,000
Pay attention.

332
00:16:27,080 --> 00:16:29,400
But Mrs Mantovani's always
my babysitter.

333
00:16:29,480 --> 00:16:31,840
Times change. Wouldn't you say?

334
00:16:31,920 --> 00:16:34,680
See? Christmas past.

335
00:16:35,600 --> 00:16:37,040
Who are you talking to?

336
00:16:37,120 --> 00:16:38,200
You.

337
00:16:38,440 --> 00:16:39,920
Now, your past is going to change.

338
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:41,560
That means your memories
will change, too.

339
00:16:41,640 --> 00:16:43,200
Bit scary,
but you'll get the hang of it.

340
00:16:43,280 --> 00:16:45,440
-I don't understand.
-I'll bet you don't.

341
00:16:45,520 --> 00:16:47,720
I wish I could see your face.

342
00:16:48,960 --> 00:16:51,000
But that never happened!

343
00:16:54,320 --> 00:16:55,720
But it did.

344
00:16:56,080 --> 00:16:57,480
Right then, your bedroom!

345
00:16:57,760 --> 00:17:00,840
Great, let's see, you're 12 years old,
so we'll stay away from under the bed.

346
00:17:00,920 --> 00:17:03,720
Cupboard! Big cupboard!
I love a cupboard.

347
00:17:04,960 --> 00:17:07,720
Do you know,
there's a thing called a face spider?

348
00:17:07,800 --> 00:17:10,440
It's just like a tiny baby's head
with spider legs.

349
00:17:10,520 --> 00:17:14,960
And it specifically evolved to scuttle
up the backs of bedroom cupboards.

350
00:17:17,600 --> 00:17:20,320
Which, yeah, I probably
shouldn't have mentioned.

351
00:17:20,400 --> 00:17:24,800
Right, so what are we going to do?
Eat crisps and talk about girls?

352
00:17:24,880 --> 00:17:28,200
I've never actually done that,
but I bet it's easy. Girls! Yeah?

353
00:17:28,280 --> 00:17:29,840
Are you really a babysitter?

354
00:17:29,920 --> 00:17:31,800
I think you'll find
I'm universally recognised

355
00:17:31,880 --> 00:17:34,160
as a mature and responsible adult.

356
00:17:35,800 --> 00:17:38,640
It's just a lot of wavy lines.

357
00:17:40,680 --> 00:17:42,480
Yeah, shorted out.
Finally, a lie too big.

358
00:17:42,560 --> 00:17:45,320
Okay, no, not really a babysitter,
but it's Christmas Eve.

359
00:17:45,400 --> 00:17:48,200
You don't want a real one. You want me.

360
00:17:48,280 --> 00:17:49,360
Why?

361
00:17:49,960 --> 00:17:51,240
What's so special about you?

362
00:17:51,320 --> 00:17:52,600
Have you ever seen Mary Poppins?

363
00:17:52,680 --> 00:17:53,760
-No.
-Good.

364
00:17:53,840 --> 00:17:55,800
Because that comparison
would have been rubbish.

365
00:17:55,880 --> 00:17:58,960
Fish in the fog. Fish in the clouds.
How do people ever get bored?

366
00:17:59,040 --> 00:18:01,840
How did boredom even get invented?

367
00:18:01,920 --> 00:18:05,400
My dad's invented a machine
to control the cloud belt.

368
00:18:05,880 --> 00:18:07,840
Tame the sky, he says.

369
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:11,120
The fish will be able to come down,
but only when we let them.

370
00:18:11,200 --> 00:18:13,040
We can charge whatever we like.

371
00:18:13,120 --> 00:18:15,600
Yeah, I've seen your dad's machine.

372
00:18:16,200 --> 00:18:18,000
What? You can't have.

373
00:18:18,240 --> 00:18:19,720
Tame the sky.

374
00:18:20,560 --> 00:18:24,160
Human beings, you always manage to
find the boring alternative, don't you?

375
00:18:24,240 --> 00:18:28,200
Do you want to see what, fish?
We can do that. We can see a fish.

376
00:18:28,320 --> 00:18:29,880
But aren't you going to tell me
it's dangerous?

377
00:18:29,960 --> 00:18:32,440
Dangerous? Come on, we're boys!

378
00:18:32,720 --> 00:18:35,360
And you know what boys say
in the face of danger.

379
00:18:35,440 --> 00:18:36,960
-What?
-"Mummy."

380
00:18:58,600 --> 00:19:00,160
YOUNG KAZRAN: Are there any
face spiders in here?

381
00:19:00,240 --> 00:19:02,880
No, not at this time of night.

382
00:19:03,920 --> 00:19:05,920
They'll all be sleeping
in your mattress.

383
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:09,040
So, why are you so interested in fish?

384
00:19:09,880 --> 00:19:11,680
'Cause they're scary.

385
00:19:11,760 --> 00:19:13,160
Good answer.

386
00:19:14,120 --> 00:19:16,560
-What kind of tie is that?
-A cool one.

387
00:19:16,640 --> 00:19:17,880
Why is it cool?

388
00:19:17,960 --> 00:19:20,600
Why are you really interested in fish?

389
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:23,360
My school.

390
00:19:24,400 --> 00:19:28,560
During the last fog belt,
the nets broke and there was an attack.

391
00:19:28,640 --> 00:19:31,240
Loads of them. A whole shoal.

392
00:19:32,280 --> 00:19:36,720
No one was hurt, but it was the most
fish ever seen below the mountains.

393
00:19:37,080 --> 00:19:38,720
Were you scared?

394
00:19:38,960 --> 00:19:40,480
I wasn't there.

395
00:19:41,240 --> 00:19:42,280
I was off sick.

396
00:19:42,360 --> 00:19:43,880
Ooh, lucky you.

397
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:48,320
Not lucky.

398
00:19:50,120 --> 00:19:54,720
It's all anyone ever talks about now.
The day the fish came.

399
00:19:56,120 --> 00:19:58,040
Everyone's got a story.

400
00:20:00,280 --> 00:20:01,760
But you don't.

401
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:06,920
I see him.

402
00:20:07,920 --> 00:20:09,360
YOUNG KAZRAN:
Why are you recording this?

403
00:20:09,440 --> 00:20:11,480
Do you pay attention at school, Kazran?

404
00:20:11,560 --> 00:20:12,680
Sorry, what?

405
00:20:12,760 --> 00:20:15,440
'Cause you're not paying attention now.

406
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:20,120
Shh.

407
00:20:21,560 --> 00:20:23,080
Now I remember.

408
00:20:24,960 --> 00:20:26,000
No, Doctor, you mustn't!

409
00:20:26,080 --> 00:20:27,120
Doctor, are you sure?

410
00:20:27,200 --> 00:20:28,240
Trust me.

411
00:20:28,320 --> 00:20:29,360
Okay.

412
00:20:29,440 --> 00:20:33,240
Oi! Eyes on the tie. Look at me.
I wear it and I don't care.

413
00:20:34,320 --> 00:20:35,400
Trust me.

414
00:20:35,560 --> 00:20:36,640
Yes.

415
00:20:36,920 --> 00:20:38,000
Yes.

416
00:20:39,200 --> 00:20:40,600
That's why it's cool.

417
00:20:56,320 --> 00:20:57,760
Hello, fishy.

418
00:20:59,640 --> 00:21:01,000
Let's see.

419
00:21:04,080 --> 00:21:05,480
Interesting.

420
00:21:06,920 --> 00:21:08,720
Crystalline fog, eh?

421
00:21:09,480 --> 00:21:12,880
Maybe carrying a tiny electrical charge.

422
00:21:13,640 --> 00:21:16,240
Is that how you fly, little fishy?

423
00:21:16,320 --> 00:21:19,120
What is it? What kind? Can I see?

424
00:21:19,480 --> 00:21:20,920
DOCTOR: Just stay there a moment.

425
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:23,120
-Is it big?
-No.

426
00:21:24,440 --> 00:21:26,160
Just a little one.

427
00:21:27,040 --> 00:21:30,120
So, little fella, what do you eat?

428
00:21:33,920 --> 00:21:34,960
How little?

429
00:21:35,040 --> 00:21:37,080
-Um...
-Can I come out?

430
00:21:37,560 --> 00:21:38,760
No, no.

431
00:21:40,040 --> 00:21:42,520
Maybe just wait there for a moment.

432
00:21:44,680 --> 00:21:45,960
YOUNG KAZRAN: Well, what colour is it?

433
00:21:46,040 --> 00:21:48,040
Big. Big colour.

434
00:21:49,600 --> 00:21:51,240
What's happening?

435
00:21:51,760 --> 00:21:53,200
Well, concentrating on the plusses,

436
00:21:53,280 --> 00:21:54,400
you've definitely got
a story of your own now.

437
00:21:54,480 --> 00:21:55,520
(DOOR BANGING)

438
00:21:55,600 --> 00:21:58,440
Also, I got a good look at the fish and
I think I understand how the fog works,

439
00:21:58,520 --> 00:22:00,080
which is going to help me
land a spaceship in the future

440
00:22:00,160 --> 00:22:01,200
and save a lot of lives.

441
00:22:01,280 --> 00:22:02,560
And I bet I'll get some
very interesting readings

442
00:22:02,640 --> 00:22:05,280
off my sonic screwdriver when I get it
back from the shark in your bedroom.

443
00:22:05,360 --> 00:22:07,000
There's a shark in my bedroom?

444
00:22:07,080 --> 00:22:08,520
Oh, fine! Focus on that!

445
00:22:08,600 --> 00:22:10,080
(DOOR BANGING)

446
00:22:12,840 --> 00:22:14,280
Has it gone?

447
00:22:15,320 --> 00:22:16,920
What's it doing?

448
00:22:19,880 --> 00:22:22,600
What do you call it
if you don't have any feet

449
00:22:22,680 --> 00:22:24,760
and you're taking a run-up?

450
00:22:27,440 --> 00:22:28,480
No!

451
00:22:34,680 --> 00:22:35,760
It's going to eat us.

452
00:22:35,840 --> 00:22:36,880
It's going to eat us.

453
00:22:36,960 --> 00:22:40,880
It's going to eat us. It's going to...
It's going to... It's going to eat us.

454
00:22:40,960 --> 00:22:44,000
Well, maybe we're going to eat it,
but I don't like the odds.

455
00:22:44,080 --> 00:22:45,760
It's stuck. Let's see.

456
00:22:45,840 --> 00:22:46,880
Tiny shark brain.

457
00:22:46,960 --> 00:22:48,600
If I had my screwdriver
I could send a pulse and stun it.

458
00:22:48,680 --> 00:22:50,160
Well, where's your screwdriver?

459
00:22:50,240 --> 00:22:52,040
Well, concentrating on the plusses...

460
00:22:52,120 --> 00:22:53,400
(ROARING)

461
00:22:54,040 --> 00:22:55,400
Within reach.

462
00:22:55,480 --> 00:22:57,720
You know, there's a real chance,
the way it's wedged in the doorway

463
00:22:57,800 --> 00:22:59,080
-is keeping its mouth open.
-There is?

464
00:22:59,160 --> 00:23:01,760
Just agree with me, 'cause I've only got
two goes and then it's your turn.

465
00:23:01,840 --> 00:23:02,920
Two goes!

466
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:05,800
Two arms! Right then, okay...

467
00:23:07,480 --> 00:23:08,760
Geronimo.

468
00:23:08,840 --> 00:23:10,120
Open wide!

469
00:23:11,680 --> 00:23:14,360
DOCTOR: What's the big fishy
done to you?

470
00:23:14,440 --> 00:23:18,360
Swallowed half of you, that's what.
Half a screwdriver? What use is that?

471
00:23:18,440 --> 00:23:20,400
Bad, big fishy.

472
00:23:21,840 --> 00:23:23,040
YOUNG KAZRAN: Doctor?

473
00:23:24,080 --> 00:23:25,840
I think she's dying.

474
00:23:27,240 --> 00:23:29,760
Half my screwdriver's still inside.

475
00:23:30,280 --> 00:23:33,240
But, yeah, I think so, I doubt they can
survive long outside the cloud belt.

476
00:23:33,320 --> 00:23:35,520
Just quick raiding trips on a

477
00:23:36,480 --> 00:23:37,840
foggy night.

478
00:23:37,920 --> 00:23:39,280
(SNIFFLING)

479
00:23:40,720 --> 00:23:42,520
Can't we get it back up there?

480
00:23:42,600 --> 00:23:45,640
We were just going to stun it.
I didn't want to kill it.

481
00:23:45,720 --> 00:23:47,760
She was trying to eat you.

482
00:23:50,320 --> 00:23:51,880
She was hungry.

483
00:23:54,160 --> 00:23:56,920
DOCTOR: I'm sorry, Kazran.
I can't save her.

484
00:23:57,720 --> 00:24:01,000
I could take her back up there,
but she'd never survive the trip.

485
00:24:03,120 --> 00:24:05,560
We'd need
a fully functioning life-support.

486
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:07,480
YOUNG KAZRAN: You mean, like an ice box?

487
00:24:07,560 --> 00:24:08,680
Okay.

488
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:17,040
DOCTOR: Oh, a tree! Look at the tree!

489
00:24:28,240 --> 00:24:29,280
(DOCTOR WHISTLING)

490
00:24:33,800 --> 00:24:35,040
DOCTOR: What is this?

491
00:24:35,120 --> 00:24:37,040
YOUNG KAZRAN: The surplus population.

492
00:24:37,360 --> 00:24:39,520
That's what my dad calls it.

493
00:24:39,600 --> 00:24:43,280
Oh, it's not turning.
We're running out of time.

494
00:24:43,760 --> 00:24:44,840
Ah, what's the number?

495
00:24:44,920 --> 00:24:46,200
7258.

496
00:24:46,280 --> 00:24:47,480
I don't know.

497
00:24:47,560 --> 00:24:49,360
The place is full of alarms.

498
00:24:49,440 --> 00:24:51,680
It's not just the door.
I need the number.

499
00:24:51,760 --> 00:24:53,040
7258!

500
00:24:53,120 --> 00:24:54,160
I need the number!

501
00:24:54,240 --> 00:24:56,040
I'm not allowed to know until I'm older.

502
00:24:56,120 --> 00:24:57,440
7258!

503
00:24:58,200 --> 00:25:00,600
Just what I was after! Thank you!

504
00:25:02,360 --> 00:25:04,920
7258!

505
00:25:05,440 --> 00:25:06,760
7258!

506
00:25:11,680 --> 00:25:13,240
(GROANING)

507
00:25:15,720 --> 00:25:17,680
Ah, there's fish down here, too.

508
00:25:17,760 --> 00:25:19,760
Yeah, but only tiny ones.

509
00:25:20,040 --> 00:25:22,880
The house is built on a fog lake.
That's how Dad freezes the people.

510
00:25:22,960 --> 00:25:25,760
They're all full,
but we could borrow one.

511
00:25:27,040 --> 00:25:28,560
Yeah, this one.

512
00:25:31,880 --> 00:25:33,280
DOCTOR: Hello again.

513
00:25:33,360 --> 00:25:34,800
YOUNG KAZRAN: You know her?

514
00:25:35,280 --> 00:25:36,600
Why, uh...

515
00:25:40,800 --> 00:25:42,520
Important, is she?

516
00:25:43,360 --> 00:25:45,840
She won't mind. She loves the fish.

517
00:25:46,680 --> 00:25:48,760
My name is Abigail Pettigrew,

518
00:25:48,840 --> 00:25:51,960
and I'm very grateful
for Mr Sardick's kindness.

519
00:25:52,280 --> 00:25:55,120
She starts to talk about the fish
in a minute.

520
00:25:55,320 --> 00:25:56,600
ABIGAIL: ...but I would not allow it.

521
00:25:56,680 --> 00:25:58,680
And I could not have chosen this path

522
00:25:58,760 --> 00:26:01,600
were it not for
the compassion and generosity

523
00:26:01,680 --> 00:26:07,000
of the great philanthropist and patron
of the poor, Mr Elliot Sardick.

524
00:26:07,680 --> 00:26:10,080
But I'm also surrounded by the fish,

525
00:26:10,160 --> 00:26:12,920
the beautiful, iridescent, magical fish.

526
00:26:13,560 --> 00:26:15,640
Why are these people here?

527
00:26:18,360 --> 00:26:20,160
What's all this for?

528
00:26:20,640 --> 00:26:21,800
My dad lends money.

529
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:24,440
He always takes a family member as...

530
00:26:24,560 --> 00:26:26,560
He calls it security.

531
00:26:28,560 --> 00:26:30,680
Hard man to love, your dad.

532
00:26:32,280 --> 00:26:34,200
I suppose you know that.

533
00:26:34,680 --> 00:26:37,560
I am not alone and I am at peace.

534
00:26:39,440 --> 00:26:41,200
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WARBLING)

535
00:26:41,280 --> 00:26:42,720
What's wrong?

536
00:26:43,880 --> 00:26:46,080
Just my half of the screwdriver
trying to repair itself.

537
00:26:46,160 --> 00:26:48,440
It's signalling the other half.

538
00:26:48,520 --> 00:26:50,120
(BEEPS APPROACHING)

539
00:26:53,720 --> 00:26:55,920
The other half's inside the shark.

540
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:57,120
Yeah.

541
00:26:58,280 --> 00:27:00,360
Sounds like she's woken up.

542
00:27:01,000 --> 00:27:03,960
Okay, so it's homing on the screwdriver.

543
00:27:04,120 --> 00:27:05,760
(ROARING)

544
00:27:08,400 --> 00:27:09,520
Run!

545
00:27:19,960 --> 00:27:21,000
Run!

546
00:27:31,280 --> 00:27:32,640
(SHARK GROWLING)

547
00:27:44,160 --> 00:27:45,280
(GASPS)

548
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:51,920
ABIGAIL: # In the bleak midwinter

549
00:27:52,440 --> 00:27:57,640
# Frosty wind made moan

550
00:27:58,840 --> 00:28:04,520
# Earth stood hard as iron

551
00:28:05,200 --> 00:28:11,200
# Water like a stone

552
00:28:11,920 --> 00:28:18,240
# Snow had fallen, snow on snow

553
00:28:18,960 --> 00:28:24,440
# Snow on snow

554
00:28:25,400 --> 00:28:31,240
# In the bleak midwinter

555
00:28:31,320 --> 00:28:37,160
# Long ago #

556
00:28:41,800 --> 00:28:44,200
-(ABIGAIL CONTINUES SINGING)
-It's not really the singing, of course.

557
00:28:44,280 --> 00:28:46,040
-Yes, it is.
-Nah.

558
00:28:46,120 --> 00:28:47,680
The fish love the singing, it's true.

559
00:28:47,760 --> 00:28:49,720
Nah, the notes resonate
in the ice crystals,

560
00:28:49,800 --> 00:28:53,240
causing a delta-wave pattern in the fog.
Ow, fish bit me!

561
00:28:53,320 --> 00:28:54,800
Shut up, then.

562
00:28:54,880 --> 00:28:57,440
# Heaven and Earth shall flee away

563
00:28:57,520 --> 00:28:59,840
Of course. That's how the machine
controls the cloud belt.

564
00:28:59,920 --> 00:29:01,960
The clouds are ice crystals.
If you could vibrate the crystals

565
00:29:02,040 --> 00:29:04,200
at exactly the right frequency,
you could align them into...

566
00:29:04,280 --> 00:29:05,760
Ow! Why do they keep biting?

567
00:29:05,840 --> 00:29:09,160
Look, the fish like the singing, okay?
Now, shut up.

568
00:29:09,240 --> 00:29:10,800
(MOUTHING)

569
00:29:10,880 --> 00:29:12,040
Okay.

570
00:29:14,400 --> 00:29:19,920
# Fall down before

571
00:29:20,280 --> 00:29:25,680
# The ox and ass and camel

572
00:29:25,760 --> 00:29:31,640
# Which adore #

573
00:29:42,160 --> 00:29:43,240
It's bigger on...

574
00:29:43,320 --> 00:29:44,360
The inside.

575
00:29:44,440 --> 00:29:47,400
Yes, the colour really
knocks the walls back.

576
00:29:47,920 --> 00:29:49,760
Shark in a box, to go.

577
00:29:53,120 --> 00:29:54,400
KAZRAN: Abigail.

578
00:29:56,480 --> 00:29:58,320
This is amazing.

579
00:29:58,720 --> 00:30:01,520
Nah, this is transport.
I keep amazing...

580
00:30:05,880 --> 00:30:06,960
Out here.

581
00:30:34,080 --> 00:30:35,160
DOCTOR: Come on, then.

582
00:30:35,480 --> 00:30:37,440
Let's get this shark out.

583
00:30:37,520 --> 00:30:38,640
(BEEPING)

584
00:30:47,800 --> 00:30:48,880
(CAMERA CLICKING)

585
00:30:57,960 --> 00:31:00,160
YOUNG KAZRAN: Wah-hey! Look at them go!

586
00:31:08,640 --> 00:31:09,720
Abigail, this number.

587
00:31:10,440 --> 00:31:11,560
What does it mean?

588
00:31:12,120 --> 00:31:13,680
It pertains to me, sir, not the fish.

589
00:31:13,760 --> 00:31:15,240
Yeah, but how?

590
00:31:16,040 --> 00:31:19,040
You are a doctor, you say?
Are you one of mine?

591
00:31:20,440 --> 00:31:21,800
Do you need a doctor?

592
00:31:22,120 --> 00:31:23,160
(TICKING)

593
00:31:23,240 --> 00:31:24,280
(BELL DINGING)

594
00:31:24,360 --> 00:31:27,200
-Ah! Sorry! Time's up, kids.
-Why?

595
00:31:27,280 --> 00:31:29,040
It's nearly Christmas day.

596
00:31:31,680 --> 00:31:33,560
If you should ever wish
to visit again...

597
00:31:33,680 --> 00:31:36,360
Well, you know,
if I'm ever in the neighbourhood.

598
00:31:36,520 --> 00:31:38,280
-He comes every Christmas Eve.
-What?

599
00:31:38,360 --> 00:31:41,200
-Yeah, he does, every time, he promises.
-No, I don't...

600
00:31:43,400 --> 00:31:44,800
-Merry Christmas!
-Merry Christmas!

601
00:31:44,880 --> 00:31:45,960
Doctor!

602
00:31:46,480 --> 00:31:47,600
ABIGAIL: What are we gonna do?

603
00:31:47,880 --> 00:31:51,120
YOUNG KAZRAN: The Doctor's got
a great plan. Wait 'til you hear.

604
00:31:57,720 --> 00:32:00,040
ABIGAIL: You are out of your mind,
this will never work.

605
00:32:00,120 --> 00:32:02,600
Oh! Don't think shark, think dolphin.

606
00:32:02,680 --> 00:32:03,720
A shark isn't a dolphin.

607
00:32:03,800 --> 00:32:05,000
-It's nearly a dolphin.
-No, it isn't.

608
00:32:05,080 --> 00:32:08,160
Well, that's where you're wrong
because... Shut up.

609
00:32:08,240 --> 00:32:09,320
Oh, it could be anywhere.

610
00:32:09,400 --> 00:32:10,760
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WARBLING)

611
00:32:10,840 --> 00:32:11,920
Will it really come?

612
00:32:12,200 --> 00:32:14,040
No chance, completely impossible.

613
00:32:15,400 --> 00:32:16,680
(BEEPS APPROACHING)

614
00:32:19,040 --> 00:32:20,200
Except at Christmas.

615
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:28,320
ABIGAIL: How are we going to get back?
DOCTOR: I don't know!

616
00:32:28,600 --> 00:32:29,640
Do you have a plan?

617
00:32:29,720 --> 00:32:30,800
Not at all!

618
00:32:34,360 --> 00:32:36,320
(ALL WHOOPING)

619
00:32:37,080 --> 00:32:38,200
(ABIGAIL SHOUTING)

620
00:33:10,400 --> 00:33:11,760
(WHOOPING)

621
00:33:18,480 --> 00:33:19,760
Best Christmas Eve ever!

622
00:33:20,080 --> 00:33:21,280
'Til the next one.

623
00:33:32,040 --> 00:33:33,160
New memories.

624
00:33:33,880 --> 00:33:35,720
How can I have new memories?

625
00:33:36,760 --> 00:33:38,120
-Merry Christmas!
-Merry Christmas!

626
00:33:38,200 --> 00:33:39,280
Doctor!

627
00:33:39,440 --> 00:33:42,120
ABIGAIL: Where to this time?
DOCTOR: Did I mention at any point

628
00:33:42,200 --> 00:33:43,280
all of time and space?

629
00:33:46,360 --> 00:33:47,800
-Merry Christmas!
-Merry Christmas!

630
00:33:47,880 --> 00:33:48,920
Doctor.

631
00:33:55,880 --> 00:33:57,440
-Merry Christmas!
-Doctor!

632
00:34:08,120 --> 00:34:09,240
-Merry Christmas!
-Merry Christmas!

633
00:34:09,320 --> 00:34:11,240
Kazran.

634
00:34:19,040 --> 00:34:20,120
ABIGAIL: You've grown.

635
00:34:20,880 --> 00:34:21,960
Yeah.

636
00:34:22,640 --> 00:34:24,400
And now you're blushing.

637
00:34:25,640 --> 00:34:27,360
-Sorry.
-That's okay.

638
00:34:28,320 --> 00:34:31,120
So, Doctor. Where this time?

639
00:34:31,200 --> 00:34:33,000
Pick a Christmas Eve,
I've got them all right here.

640
00:34:33,080 --> 00:34:34,320
Might I make a request?

641
00:34:36,720 --> 00:34:37,840
Of course.

642
00:34:38,880 --> 00:34:40,240
This one.

643
00:34:43,680 --> 00:34:45,040
(PEOPLE CHATTERING SOFTLY)

644
00:34:49,080 --> 00:34:50,160
MAN: Thank you, darling.

645
00:34:53,880 --> 00:34:55,560
-Who are they?
-Her family.

646
00:34:56,720 --> 00:35:00,880
The lady"s her sister.
I met her once when she was older.

647
00:35:05,840 --> 00:35:06,960
Abigail's crying.

648
00:35:08,880 --> 00:35:09,960
Yes.

649
00:35:11,280 --> 00:35:14,640
When girls are crying,
are you supposed to talk to them?

650
00:35:17,040 --> 00:35:19,680
I have absolutely no idea.

651
00:35:33,840 --> 00:35:34,960
My sister's family.

652
00:35:36,160 --> 00:35:37,880
ABIGAIL: They're so happy.

653
00:35:38,960 --> 00:35:40,040
They look very poor.

654
00:35:40,160 --> 00:35:41,280
They are very poor.

655
00:35:41,400 --> 00:35:43,000
Doesn't mean you can't be happy.

656
00:35:44,040 --> 00:35:45,080
MAN: Close the curtains.

657
00:35:45,160 --> 00:35:46,200
Then why aren't you?

658
00:35:51,280 --> 00:35:53,440
Because this is the life
I can never have.

659
00:35:54,600 --> 00:35:55,680
Why not?

660
00:36:02,480 --> 00:36:03,760
I think you're blushing again.

661
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:08,120
DOCTOR: Come in!

662
00:36:11,560 --> 00:36:13,360
Pick a card. Any card at all.

663
00:36:13,680 --> 00:36:15,000
Every Christmas Eve?

664
00:36:15,080 --> 00:36:17,320
-I don't understand.
-I'm not sure I do.

665
00:36:17,720 --> 00:36:19,560
DOCTOR: You memorise a card,
you put it back in the deck.

666
00:36:19,640 --> 00:36:21,120
Don't let me see it.

667
00:36:21,720 --> 00:36:23,240
Is this what it looked like last year?

668
00:36:23,600 --> 00:36:25,520
Well, it doesn't have to be
exactly the same.

669
00:36:27,200 --> 00:36:29,760
I'm starting again.
Come on, Kazran. We're starting again.

670
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:32,720
That's Sardick's boy, isn't it.

671
00:36:32,800 --> 00:36:34,200
He's not like his father.

672
00:36:34,280 --> 00:36:36,400
His father treats everyone like cattle.

673
00:36:36,960 --> 00:36:38,680
-One day that boy will do the same.
-No.

674
00:36:39,480 --> 00:36:40,560
He's different.

675
00:36:40,640 --> 00:36:42,160
Three of clubs.

676
00:36:42,240 --> 00:36:43,320
No.

677
00:36:43,920 --> 00:36:45,680
You sure?
Because I'm very good at card tricks.

678
00:36:45,760 --> 00:36:46,800
It wasn't the three of clubs.

679
00:36:46,880 --> 00:36:50,160
Well, of course it wasn't,
because it was the seven of diamonds.

680
00:36:50,400 --> 00:36:53,160
-No.
-0i, stop it, you're doing it wrong.

681
00:36:53,560 --> 00:36:55,320
I see him around the town sometimes.

682
00:36:55,400 --> 00:36:57,240
-Never any friends.
-He's got me.

683
00:36:57,720 --> 00:36:59,440
All those Christmas Eves...

684
00:36:59,720 --> 00:37:01,160
You never once came to see us.

685
00:37:01,240 --> 00:37:02,400
I'm here now.

686
00:37:02,480 --> 00:37:04,640
Then stay! Stay for tomorrow.

687
00:37:04,720 --> 00:37:06,400
Have Christmas dinner with us.

688
00:37:07,120 --> 00:37:08,200
I can't.

689
00:37:09,360 --> 00:37:10,400
Well, then.

690
00:37:11,880 --> 00:37:13,440
Tomorrow's Christmas dinner
is cancelled,

691
00:37:13,520 --> 00:37:15,680
-as my sister refuses to attend.
-Isabella!

692
00:37:15,760 --> 00:37:18,880
Instead, we'll have it tonight.

693
00:37:20,720 --> 00:37:23,160
Three, two, one, pull!

694
00:37:23,760 --> 00:37:24,920
(ALL CHEERING)

695
00:37:27,760 --> 00:37:29,200
How did you do that?

696
00:37:29,800 --> 00:37:30,960
Your card, I believe.

697
00:37:31,520 --> 00:37:33,080
No.

698
00:37:34,600 --> 00:37:35,960
Oh, shut up.

699
00:37:36,080 --> 00:37:37,120
(ALL LAUGHING)

700
00:37:39,400 --> 00:37:42,200
-Merry Christmas.
-ALL: Merry Christmas.

701
00:37:50,600 --> 00:37:52,760
Best Christmas Eve ever.

702
00:37:52,840 --> 00:37:53,920
Ah! 'Til the next one.

703
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:56,840
I look forward to it.
Now I'd like to say goodnight to Kazran.

704
00:37:56,920 --> 00:37:58,040
Of course, yes.

705
00:38:00,240 --> 00:38:01,320
Well, on you go.

706
00:38:03,480 --> 00:38:06,600
Oh, oh. Yes, right. Sorry.

707
00:38:07,440 --> 00:38:08,520
I'll... I'll go, then.

708
00:38:08,800 --> 00:38:10,960
Good night. Good luck... Night.

709
00:38:11,640 --> 00:38:12,680
Good night.

710
00:38:13,760 --> 00:38:15,480
-(CRASHING)
-Sorry.

711
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:22,760
Doctor. I think she's going to kiss me.

712
00:38:22,840 --> 00:38:24,240
Yeah, I think you're right.

713
00:38:25,120 --> 00:38:26,200
(KAZRAN GROANS)

714
00:38:27,840 --> 00:38:30,880
I've never kissed anyone before.
What do I do?

715
00:38:30,960 --> 00:38:32,040
Well,

716
00:38:32,840 --> 00:38:34,760
try and be all nervous and rubbish
and a bit shaky.

717
00:38:34,840 --> 00:38:36,000
-Why?
-Because you're gonna be

718
00:38:36,080 --> 00:38:37,720
like that anyway,
might as well make it part of the plan,

719
00:38:37,800 --> 00:38:39,440
then it will feel on purpose.
Off you go, then.

720
00:38:39,840 --> 00:38:41,800
KAZRAN: (SOFTLY) Now? I kiss her now?

721
00:38:41,880 --> 00:38:43,720
Kazran, trust me,
it's this or going to your room

722
00:38:43,800 --> 00:38:46,280
and designing a new kind of screwdriver.
Don't make my mistakes.

723
00:38:46,360 --> 00:38:47,440
Now, go!

724
00:39:34,280 --> 00:39:36,280
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

725
00:39:39,200 --> 00:39:41,200
(JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

726
00:39:42,160 --> 00:39:43,560
KAZRAN: Abigail.

727
00:39:43,640 --> 00:39:44,960
Are you coming back?

728
00:39:45,400 --> 00:39:47,600
The Doctor is gonna do a duet
with Frank.

729
00:39:50,120 --> 00:39:51,200
Abigail?

730
00:39:53,400 --> 00:39:54,440
What's wrong?

731
00:39:57,520 --> 00:39:58,800
I have something to tell you.

732
00:40:00,480 --> 00:40:01,520
A bad thing?

733
00:40:03,920 --> 00:40:05,640
A very bad thing.

734
00:40:08,480 --> 00:40:10,200
What is it?

735
00:40:11,640 --> 00:40:12,720
(SIGHING)

736
00:40:13,720 --> 00:40:14,760
The truth...

737
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:19,080
Guys!

738
00:40:19,160 --> 00:40:22,080
We've really got to go quite quickly,
I just accidentally got engaged

739
00:40:22,160 --> 00:40:23,280
to Marilyn Monroe.

740
00:40:23,360 --> 00:40:25,200
(STUTTERING)

741
00:40:25,280 --> 00:40:26,360
Is...

742
00:40:27,760 --> 00:40:31,040
How do you keep going like that?
Do you breathe out your ears?

743
00:40:31,120 --> 00:40:32,320
Hello? Sorry.

744
00:40:32,400 --> 00:40:35,560
Hello? Guys, she's phoned a chapel,

745
00:40:35,640 --> 00:40:38,240
there's a car outside,
this is happening now.

746
00:40:38,640 --> 00:40:40,600
MARILYN: Yoo-hoo!
DOCTOR: Yoo-hoo.

747
00:40:40,680 --> 00:40:42,160
(SIGHING) Right.

748
00:40:42,240 --> 00:40:45,080
Fine, thank you. I'll just go
and get married then, shall I?

749
00:40:45,440 --> 00:40:46,840
See how you like that.

750
00:40:48,440 --> 00:40:51,000
Marilyn, get your coat!

751
00:40:54,120 --> 00:40:55,440
What are we going to do?

752
00:40:56,520 --> 00:40:58,680
(CRYING) There is nothing to be done.

753
00:41:03,000 --> 00:41:04,040
(BEEPING)

754
00:41:09,040 --> 00:41:10,360
Good night, Abigail.

755
00:41:12,800 --> 00:41:13,880
Good night, Kazran.

756
00:41:34,280 --> 00:41:35,360
(INHALES SHARPLY)

757
00:41:35,760 --> 00:41:38,080
Here we go, another day,
another Christmas Eve.

758
00:41:38,160 --> 00:41:40,200
I'll see you in a minute, okay?
I mean, a year.

759
00:41:40,280 --> 00:41:41,360
Doctor?

760
00:41:43,640 --> 00:41:44,920
Listen, why don't we leave it?

761
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:46,600
Sorry? Leave what?

762
00:41:46,680 --> 00:41:50,680
You know, this. Every Christmas Eve,
it's getting a bit old.

763
00:41:51,800 --> 00:41:52,880
Old?

764
00:41:53,440 --> 00:41:55,920
Well, Christmas is for kids, isn't it?

765
00:41:56,880 --> 00:41:59,520
I've got some work with my dad now,
I'm going to focus on that.

766
00:42:01,400 --> 00:42:02,720
Get that cloud belt under control.

767
00:42:03,440 --> 00:42:06,560
Sorry, I didn't realise
I was boring you.

768
00:42:07,160 --> 00:42:08,720
Not your fault.

769
00:42:08,800 --> 00:42:09,920
Times change.

770
00:42:13,120 --> 00:42:14,600
Not as much as I'd hoped.

771
00:42:15,760 --> 00:42:16,800
Kazran.

772
00:42:20,400 --> 00:42:22,040
I'll be needing a new one, anyway.

773
00:42:22,800 --> 00:42:24,040
What the hell.

774
00:42:25,680 --> 00:42:26,760
Merry Christmas.

775
00:42:27,400 --> 00:42:29,720
And if you ever need me,
just activate it, I'll hear you.

776
00:42:29,800 --> 00:42:30,840
I won't need you.

777
00:42:34,840 --> 00:42:36,800
What's happened?
What are you not telling me?

778
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:43,040
What about Abigail?

779
00:42:45,040 --> 00:42:46,360
I know where to find her.

780
00:42:48,200 --> 00:42:49,280
(SOFTLY) Nah.

781
00:43:03,360 --> 00:43:04,480
(DOOR LOCKING)

782
00:43:16,280 --> 00:43:18,720
ELLIOT: Another Christmas Eve, Kazran.

783
00:43:19,440 --> 00:43:21,840
But a very special one.

784
00:43:21,920 --> 00:43:24,160
It's complete, look at it!

785
00:43:24,400 --> 00:43:27,520
Sound waves. It's as simple as that.

786
00:43:27,600 --> 00:43:31,080
We can control the clouds,
the fog, the fish.

787
00:43:31,680 --> 00:43:33,360
Why do we want to control the fish?

788
00:43:33,440 --> 00:43:34,480
People are cattle.

789
00:43:34,560 --> 00:43:38,240
If you want to control cattle,
you need to control their predators.

790
00:43:39,280 --> 00:43:40,680
What's the face for?

791
00:43:41,240 --> 00:43:42,360
Look what I'm giving you.

792
00:43:42,800 --> 00:43:46,640
The sky and everything beneath it.

793
00:43:47,720 --> 00:43:50,120
Only you and I can control this.

794
00:43:50,200 --> 00:43:53,280
This planet is ours.

795
00:43:54,760 --> 00:43:56,160
Excuse me, Father.

796
00:44:58,400 --> 00:44:59,920
(PHONE RINGING)

797
00:45:00,800 --> 00:45:01,920
Yes, what?

798
00:45:02,920 --> 00:45:06,320
Oh, Mr President,
we've been through this.

799
00:45:06,400 --> 00:45:09,920
It's not going to crash on my house
so what's it got to do with me?

800
00:45:10,480 --> 00:45:13,160
Yes, I know, 4,003.

801
00:45:13,680 --> 00:45:17,040
As a very old friend of mine
once took a very long time to explain,

802
00:45:17,600 --> 00:45:19,240
life isn't fair!

803
00:45:31,640 --> 00:45:32,760
Hello.

804
00:45:33,240 --> 00:45:34,400
Who are you? What are you doing here?

805
00:45:34,720 --> 00:45:38,160
You didn't think this was over, did you?
I'm the Ghost of Christmas Present.

806
00:45:38,760 --> 00:45:41,200
A ghost? Dressed like that?

807
00:45:42,880 --> 00:45:44,000
Eyes off the skirt.

808
00:45:45,680 --> 00:45:48,040
-You turned into a Roman.
-Yeah, yeah, I do that.

809
00:45:48,120 --> 00:45:50,840
-I also do this.
-Do what?

810
00:45:51,720 --> 00:45:52,880
What are you talking about?

811
00:45:54,240 --> 00:45:56,680
(FAINTLY) # Silent night

812
00:45:57,240 --> 00:46:00,680
# Holy night

813
00:46:01,160 --> 00:46:03,480
# All is calm

814
00:46:05,080 --> 00:46:08,400
# All is bright

815
00:46:09,360 --> 00:46:14,520
# Round yon virgin mother and child

816
00:46:14,600 --> 00:46:15,960
(BEEPING)

817
00:46:16,560 --> 00:46:22,960
# Holy infant so tender and mild

818
00:46:24,720 --> 00:46:29,720
# Christ the Saviour is born

819
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:35,680
# Christ the Saviour is born #

820
00:46:36,960 --> 00:46:39,360
They're holograms. Projections, like me.

821
00:46:39,560 --> 00:46:40,680
Who are they?

822
00:46:41,080 --> 00:46:42,320
The people in the ship up there,

823
00:46:42,400 --> 00:46:44,520
the ones that you're going
to let die tonight.

824
00:46:45,640 --> 00:46:47,000
Why are they singing?

825
00:46:48,200 --> 00:46:49,280
For their lives.

826
00:46:51,640 --> 00:46:52,720
Which one's Abigail?

827
00:46:54,240 --> 00:46:56,440
-The Doctor told me.
-Did he now?

828
00:46:56,520 --> 00:46:58,040
Well, he doesn't hold back,
you know the Doctor.

829
00:46:58,440 --> 00:47:00,480
How do I?
I never met him before tonight.

830
00:47:01,160 --> 00:47:03,560
Now I seem to have known him
all my life. How? Why?

831
00:47:03,960 --> 00:47:06,040
You're the only person
who can let that ship land.

832
00:47:07,040 --> 00:47:10,160
He was trying to turn you
into a nicer person.

833
00:47:11,080 --> 00:47:12,840
But he was trying to do it nicely.

834
00:47:13,520 --> 00:47:16,320
He's changed my past, my whole life.

835
00:47:16,400 --> 00:47:18,120
Time can be rewritten.

836
00:47:18,200 --> 00:47:21,880
You tell the Doctor,
tell him from me, people can't!

837
00:47:32,160 --> 00:47:33,200
AMY: That's Abigail.

838
00:47:33,600 --> 00:47:35,440
I would never have known her
if the Doctor hadn't

839
00:47:35,520 --> 00:47:39,000
changed the course of my whole life
to suit himself.

840
00:47:39,080 --> 00:47:40,320
Well, that's good, isn't it?

841
00:47:40,400 --> 00:47:41,520
No.

842
00:47:43,360 --> 00:47:45,640
Why is she still in there?
You could let her out any time.

843
00:47:45,960 --> 00:47:47,000
Oh, yes.

844
00:47:47,280 --> 00:47:51,600
Any time at all. Any time I choose.

845
00:47:51,760 --> 00:47:52,840
AMY: Then why don't you?

846
00:47:54,920 --> 00:47:56,680
This is what the Doctor did to me.

847
00:47:57,840 --> 00:48:01,120
Abigail was ill when she went into
the ice, on the point of death.

848
00:48:02,600 --> 00:48:04,760
I suppose the rest in the ice helped her

849
00:48:06,080 --> 00:48:08,000
but she's used up her time.

850
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:12,200
All those Christmas Eves with me.

851
00:48:14,320 --> 00:48:17,080
I could release her any time I want

852
00:48:19,360 --> 00:48:22,120
and she would live a single day.

853
00:48:22,800 --> 00:48:25,040
So tell me, Ghost of Christmas Present,

854
00:48:26,160 --> 00:48:28,000
how do I choose which day?

855
00:48:30,120 --> 00:48:31,400
I'm sorry.

856
00:48:31,480 --> 00:48:33,240
(STAMMERING) I really am, I'm very...

857
00:48:34,560 --> 00:48:35,640
Very sorry.

858
00:48:36,440 --> 00:48:38,440
But you know what?
She's got more time left than I have.

859
00:48:38,520 --> 00:48:39,640
More than anyone on this ship.

860
00:48:39,720 --> 00:48:40,760
Good.

861
00:48:40,840 --> 00:48:42,640
Rory, widen the beam.

862
00:48:45,200 --> 00:48:46,720
(ALARM BLARING)

863
00:48:47,920 --> 00:48:49,200
CAPTAIN: Major update on engine one.

864
00:48:49,280 --> 00:48:50,880
KAZRAN: How did I get here?

865
00:48:51,040 --> 00:48:53,280
You didn't.
It's your turn to be the hologram.

866
00:48:53,440 --> 00:48:55,520
Since you're going to let a lot of
people die tonight,

867
00:48:55,600 --> 00:48:57,560
I thought you might like to see
where it's all going to happen.

868
00:48:57,640 --> 00:48:58,680
# All is bright

869
00:48:58,760 --> 00:49:00,160
The singing.

870
00:49:00,920 --> 00:49:01,960
What is it?

871
00:49:03,160 --> 00:49:04,200
I don't understand.

872
00:49:04,280 --> 00:49:06,920
It's the Doctor's idea. The harmonies
resonate in the ice crystals,

873
00:49:07,000 --> 00:49:08,400
that's why the fish like it.

874
00:49:08,480 --> 00:49:09,560
(CRASHING)

875
00:49:09,640 --> 00:49:13,160
He thought that maybe it would
stabilise the ship but it isn't working.

876
00:49:13,240 --> 00:49:14,600
It's not powerful enough.

877
00:49:14,680 --> 00:49:16,240
Why are they still singing, then?

878
00:49:16,320 --> 00:49:17,360
Because we haven't told them.

879
00:49:19,440 --> 00:49:23,160
Sir, I understand you have a machine
that controls this cloud layer.

880
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:27,080
If you can release us from it,
we still have time to make a landing.

881
00:49:27,160 --> 00:49:28,440
Nobody has to die.

882
00:49:28,520 --> 00:49:30,640
Everybody has to die.

883
00:49:30,720 --> 00:49:32,960
-Not tonight.
-Tonight's as good as any other night.

884
00:49:34,760 --> 00:49:35,920
How do you choose?

885
00:49:37,560 --> 00:49:38,880
-Doctor?
-DOCTOR: Yeah?

886
00:49:38,960 --> 00:49:40,680
-Are you hearing this?
-I can hear.

887
00:49:40,760 --> 00:49:43,360
He's here. Where is he?

888
00:49:43,680 --> 00:49:44,800
Doctor!

889
00:49:44,880 --> 00:49:45,960
Doctor!

890
00:49:48,080 --> 00:49:49,400
DOCTOR: I'm sorry.

891
00:49:50,200 --> 00:49:51,560
I didn't realise.

892
00:49:51,640 --> 00:49:54,040
All my life I've been called heartless.

893
00:49:54,440 --> 00:49:57,760
My other life, my real life,
the one you rewrote.

894
00:49:57,880 --> 00:49:59,000
Now look at me.

895
00:50:00,760 --> 00:50:03,120
Better a broken heart
than no heart at all.

896
00:50:03,200 --> 00:50:05,040
Try it. You try it.

897
00:50:07,400 --> 00:50:09,920
-Why are you here?
-Because I'm not finished with you yet.

898
00:50:10,880 --> 00:50:13,800
You've seen the past, present

899
00:50:15,440 --> 00:50:17,360
and now you need to see the future.

900
00:50:17,440 --> 00:50:18,960
Fine, do it. Show me.

901
00:50:19,320 --> 00:50:21,600
I'll die cold, alone and afraid.

902
00:50:21,680 --> 00:50:23,040
Of course I will, we all do.

903
00:50:23,680 --> 00:50:25,400
What difference does showing me make?

904
00:50:27,360 --> 00:50:29,320
Do you know why I'm going to let
those people die?

905
00:50:30,120 --> 00:50:32,400
Not a plan,
I don't get anything from it.

906
00:50:33,560 --> 00:50:35,200
It's just that I don't care.

907
00:50:35,280 --> 00:50:38,160
I'm not like you,
I don't even want to be like you.

908
00:50:38,680 --> 00:50:41,560
I don't and never, ever will care.

909
00:50:45,920 --> 00:50:47,280
And I don't believe that.

910
00:50:47,640 --> 00:50:50,120
Then show me the future, prove me wrong.

911
00:50:50,200 --> 00:50:52,920
I am showing it to you,
I'm showing it to you right now.

912
00:50:55,920 --> 00:50:57,320
So what do you think?

913
00:51:03,080 --> 00:51:05,240
Is this who you want to become, Kazran?

914
00:51:15,960 --> 00:51:17,040
Dad?

915
00:51:22,640 --> 00:51:23,760
This planet is ours.

916
00:51:26,280 --> 00:51:27,320
(INAUDIBLE)

917
00:51:28,640 --> 00:51:29,720
(GASPING)

918
00:51:35,560 --> 00:51:37,160
(CRYING)

919
00:51:41,160 --> 00:51:44,560
I'm sorry, I'm so, so sorry.
It's okay to be frightened.

920
00:51:48,440 --> 00:51:51,680
I'm so, so sorry.

921
00:51:52,960 --> 00:51:54,080
(BOTH CRYING)

922
00:51:57,760 --> 00:51:58,800
Kazran,

923
00:52:04,280 --> 00:52:06,040
we don't have much time.

924
00:52:08,320 --> 00:52:09,360
Structural integrity at 30%.

925
00:52:09,480 --> 00:52:12,400
We have five minutes, max,
we need to land!

926
00:52:14,240 --> 00:52:17,560
DOCTOR: Hello? Hello?
Ah, hello everyone!

927
00:52:17,640 --> 00:52:19,000
Prepare to lock on to my signal.

928
00:52:19,200 --> 00:52:20,240
Doctor, what's happening?

929
00:52:20,320 --> 00:52:22,400
I just saved Christmas. Don't go away.

930
00:52:23,520 --> 00:52:25,800
Doctor? Doctor!

931
00:52:25,880 --> 00:52:26,960
We good to go?

932
00:52:27,040 --> 00:52:28,400
The controls, they won't respond.

933
00:52:28,480 --> 00:52:31,080
Of course they will, they're isomorphic,
they're tuned to your brain waves,

934
00:52:31,160 --> 00:52:32,360
-they'll only respond to you.
-They don't respond.

935
00:52:32,440 --> 00:52:33,760
Well, that doesn't make sense.

936
00:52:33,840 --> 00:52:35,080
That's ridiculous, why would...

937
00:52:39,160 --> 00:52:41,760
Oh. Oh, of course.

938
00:52:41,840 --> 00:52:44,280
Stupid, stupid Doctor.

939
00:52:44,360 --> 00:52:46,960
-What's wrong, tell me, what is it?
-It's you.

940
00:52:47,760 --> 00:52:50,360
It's you. I've changed you too much.
The machine doesn't recognise you.

941
00:52:50,440 --> 00:52:51,760
I know my father programmed it...

942
00:52:51,840 --> 00:52:55,320
No, your father would never have
programmed it for the man you are now.

943
00:52:55,880 --> 00:52:58,000
-Then what do we do?
-Um...

944
00:52:58,840 --> 00:53:00,560
Um... I don't know, I don't know.

945
00:53:00,640 --> 00:53:01,760
There must be something.

946
00:53:02,840 --> 00:53:04,560
This. You can use this, I kept it, see?

947
00:53:04,640 --> 00:53:06,000
What, half a screwdriver?

948
00:53:09,840 --> 00:53:11,840
With the other half up in the sky
in a big old shark

949
00:53:11,920 --> 00:53:14,080
right in the heart of the cloud layer.

950
00:53:15,240 --> 00:53:18,240
If we use your aerial to boost the
signal and set up a resonation pattern

951
00:53:18,320 --> 00:53:20,520
between the two halves...
Oh, come on, that would work.

952
00:53:20,600 --> 00:53:22,880
My screwdriver, coolest bit of kit
on this planet, coolest two bits,

953
00:53:22,960 --> 00:53:24,640
-it could do it.
-Do what?

954
00:53:24,720 --> 00:53:28,320
While my screwdriver's still trying to
repair, it's signalling itself.

955
00:53:28,400 --> 00:53:30,160
We use the signal
but we send something else.

956
00:53:30,760 --> 00:53:31,800
Send what?

957
00:53:32,960 --> 00:53:34,080
Well, what? What?

958
00:53:38,520 --> 00:53:39,640
I'm sorry, Kazran.

959
00:53:40,360 --> 00:53:41,440
I truly am.

960
00:53:42,040 --> 00:53:43,280
I don't understand.

961
00:53:43,360 --> 00:53:47,640
We need to transmit something into
the cloud belt, something we know works.

962
00:53:49,960 --> 00:53:51,280
We need her to sing.

963
00:53:55,640 --> 00:53:57,720
DOCTOR: Her voice resonates perfectly
with the ice crystals,

964
00:53:57,800 --> 00:54:00,560
it calmed the shark,
it will calm the sky too.

965
00:54:01,320 --> 00:54:02,400
Could you do it?

966
00:54:03,680 --> 00:54:05,120
Could you do this?

967
00:54:06,120 --> 00:54:07,480
Think about it, Doctor.

968
00:54:08,520 --> 00:54:10,200
One last day with your beloved.

969
00:54:10,840 --> 00:54:12,320
Which day would you choose?

970
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:15,040
(DOOR UNLOCKING)

971
00:54:15,120 --> 00:54:16,160
ABIGAIL: Christmas.

972
00:54:17,440 --> 00:54:19,240
-Christmas Day.
-(GASPING)

973
00:54:20,040 --> 00:54:21,120
Look at you.

974
00:54:22,400 --> 00:54:23,960
You're so old now.

975
00:54:24,840 --> 00:54:27,160
I think you waited a bit too long,
didn't you?

976
00:54:27,240 --> 00:54:30,040
-I'm sorry.
-Hoarding my days like an old miser.

977
00:54:30,360 --> 00:54:31,440
(LAUGHING)

978
00:54:32,040 --> 00:54:35,240
But if you leave the ice now...

979
00:54:35,440 --> 00:54:37,600
We've had so many
Christmas Eves, Kazran,

980
00:54:38,440 --> 00:54:41,000
I think it's time for Christmas Day.

981
00:54:43,280 --> 00:54:44,400
Doctor!

982
00:54:44,960 --> 00:54:46,920
We can't hold this! Time's up!
We're going down.

983
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:48,120
Doctor!

984
00:54:53,040 --> 00:54:54,160
Captain, I've got...

985
00:54:54,560 --> 00:54:55,600
I don't know what I've got.

986
00:54:57,080 --> 00:54:58,120
(ABIGAIL SINGING OVER INTERCOM)

987
00:54:58,200 --> 00:54:59,560
What is that? What are you listening to?

988
00:55:00,200 --> 00:55:01,320
This is coming from outside.

989
00:55:01,840 --> 00:55:03,200
This is coming from the actual clouds.

990
00:55:07,040 --> 00:55:08,160
(ABIGAIL SINGING)

991
00:55:22,440 --> 00:55:25,960
# When you're alone

992
00:55:26,640 --> 00:55:32,160
# Silence is all you know

993
00:55:32,720 --> 00:55:34,000
-Well?
-Well?

994
00:55:34,920 --> 00:55:37,440
The singing resonates in the crystals,
it's feeding back and forth

995
00:55:37,520 --> 00:55:39,360
between the two halves
of the screwdriver now.

996
00:55:39,440 --> 00:55:41,680
One song filling the sky.

997
00:55:41,760 --> 00:55:44,280
The crystals will align
and I'll feed in a control phase loop

998
00:55:44,360 --> 00:55:45,840
and the clouds will unlock.

999
00:55:45,920 --> 00:55:47,400
What does that mean? Unlock?

1000
00:55:47,480 --> 00:55:49,320
What happens when a cloud unlocks?

1001
00:55:49,680 --> 00:55:52,600
Something that hasn't happened
in this town for a very long time now.

1002
00:55:55,040 --> 00:55:58,800
# When you're alone

1003
00:55:59,680 --> 00:56:05,560
# Silence is all you see

1004
00:56:09,760 --> 00:56:12,720
# When you're alone

1005
00:56:14,480 --> 00:56:18,960
# Silence is all you'll be

1006
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:30,640
# Give me your hand
Oh come to me

1007
00:56:30,720 --> 00:56:31,840
We're flying normally.

1008
00:56:32,280 --> 00:56:33,400
Can you land?

1009
00:56:33,960 --> 00:56:35,080
I can even land well.

1010
00:56:38,640 --> 00:56:39,720
Oh, he did it.

1011
00:56:40,320 --> 00:56:41,400
The Doctor did it.

1012
00:56:41,840 --> 00:56:43,720
Yeah, he gets all the credit.

1013
00:56:44,680 --> 00:56:47,040
Which is actually fair enough,
if you think about it.

1014
00:56:47,120 --> 00:56:48,320
(AMY CHUCKLING)

1015
00:57:04,200 --> 00:57:06,960
# When you are here

1016
00:57:08,080 --> 00:57:12,640
# Music is all around

1017
00:57:18,040 --> 00:57:21,360
# When you are near

1018
00:57:22,920 --> 00:57:27,560
# Music is all around

1019
00:57:32,920 --> 00:57:35,640
# Open your eyes

1020
00:57:37,760 --> 00:57:43,440
# Don't make a sound

1021
00:57:44,800 --> 00:57:45,960
Hello, my old friend.

1022
00:57:47,880 --> 00:57:51,840
# Let in the shadow

1023
00:57:51,920 --> 00:57:53,000
Let's go.

1024
00:57:53,080 --> 00:57:57,640
# Let in the shadow

1025
00:57:58,040 --> 00:58:00,320
# Let in the light

1026
00:58:00,400 --> 00:58:06,200
# Of your bright shadow

1027
00:58:07,640 --> 00:58:11,640
# Let in the shadow

1028
00:58:14,240 --> 00:58:16,480
(WHOOSHING)

1029
00:58:17,600 --> 00:58:20,080
# Let in the light

1030
00:58:20,160 --> 00:58:26,400
# Of your bright shadow #

1031
00:58:27,400 --> 00:58:29,560
AMY: You know, that could almost
be mistaken for a real person.

1032
00:58:30,280 --> 00:58:31,320
Snowman isn't bad either.

1033
00:58:31,560 --> 00:58:34,640
Ah, yes, you two, about time.
Why are you dressed like that?

1034
00:58:34,800 --> 00:58:37,000
(STAMMERING) I kind of lost our luggage.

1035
00:58:37,440 --> 00:58:38,720
Kind of crash landed?

1036
00:58:38,800 --> 00:58:40,680
Yeah, but why are you
dressed like that at all?

1037
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:43,120
Yeah, they really love their snowmen
around here, don't they?

1038
00:58:43,200 --> 00:58:44,280
I've counted about 20.

1039
00:58:44,360 --> 00:58:45,720
Yeah, I've been busy.

1040
00:58:46,080 --> 00:58:47,880
Yeah. Yeah, you have.

1041
00:58:49,240 --> 00:58:50,400
Thank you.

1042
00:58:50,480 --> 00:58:52,520
Pleasure. Right.
Come on, then. Let's go.

1043
00:58:52,600 --> 00:58:55,720
Got any more honeymoon ideas?

1044
00:58:55,800 --> 00:58:58,560
Well, there's a moon that's made of
actual honey, well, not actual honey.

1045
00:58:58,640 --> 00:59:00,520
And it's not actually a moon,

1046
00:59:00,600 --> 00:59:02,560
and technically it's alive
and a bit carnivorous

1047
00:59:02,640 --> 00:59:04,480
but there are some lovely views.

1048
00:59:04,720 --> 00:59:07,520
Yeah? Great. Thanks.

1049
00:59:09,080 --> 00:59:11,000
Are you... Are you okay?

1050
00:59:11,080 --> 00:59:12,840
-Of course I'm okay. You?
-Of course.

1051
00:59:14,760 --> 00:59:16,320
It'll be their last day together,
won't it?

1052
00:59:19,560 --> 00:59:20,840
Everything's got to end sometime.

1053
00:59:20,920 --> 00:59:22,960
Otherwise,
nothing would ever get started.

1054
00:59:23,680 --> 00:59:26,520
Uh, your phone was ringing.
Someone called Marilyn.

1055
00:59:27,240 --> 00:59:29,240
Actually sounds like "the" Marilyn.

1056
00:59:29,320 --> 00:59:30,480
Doctor?

1057
00:59:30,560 --> 00:59:34,680
Tell her I'll phone her back
and that was never a real chapel.

1058
00:59:37,680 --> 00:59:39,640
Where are they? Kazran and Abigail.

1059
00:59:39,760 --> 00:59:41,320
Off on a little trip, I should think.

1060
00:59:41,400 --> 00:59:42,960
-Where?
-Christmas.

1061
00:59:43,040 --> 00:59:44,200
Christmas?

1062
00:59:44,320 --> 00:59:46,440
Yeah, Christmas.

1063
00:59:53,000 --> 00:59:55,000
Halfway out of the dark.

1064
01:00:44,760 --> 01:00:45,840
Where's the Doctor?

1065
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:48,000
DOCTOR: I've been running,

1066
01:00:49,040 --> 01:00:50,240
faster than I've ever run.

1067
01:00:50,960 --> 01:00:52,400
Now it's time for me to stop.

1068
01:00:53,480 --> 01:00:55,440
I'm going to need a SWAT team
ready to mobilise,

1069
01:00:55,520 --> 01:00:57,000
street-level maps
covering all of Florida,

1070
01:00:57,080 --> 01:00:59,360
pot of coffee,
12 Jammie Dodgers and a fez.

1071
01:01:00,680 --> 01:01:03,560
DOCTOR: Somewhere different
somewhere brand new.

1072
01:01:04,800 --> 01:01:08,160
I wear a Stetson now.
Stetson's are cool.

1073
01:01:08,240 --> 01:01:09,240
(GUNSHOT)

1074
01:01:09,360 --> 01:01:10,600
RIVER: We've been recruited.

1075
01:01:11,160 --> 01:01:12,160
DOCTOR: Recruited by who?

1076
01:01:12,960 --> 01:01:14,440
RIVER: You're going to have to
trust us this time.

1077
01:01:14,520 --> 01:01:17,000
AMY: You have to do this
and you can't ask why.

1078
01:01:25,320 --> 01:01:26,560
(SCREAMING)

1079
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:28,360
My life in your hands.

1080
01:01:28,840 --> 01:01:29,840
Amelia Pond.

1081
01:01:31,240 --> 01:01:34,320
See these eyes? They're old eyes.

1082
01:01:34,640 --> 01:01:36,280
And one thing I can tell you,

1083
01:01:38,840 --> 01:01:40,000
monsters are real.

